{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17612697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17612697"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:27:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:27:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16283"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16283","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16283"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.65,0.06,0,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8974"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66844"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8974"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16283"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52298"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"379"},{"type":"tags","id":"1153"},{"type":"tags","id":"1966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"7553"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21353"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21357"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22345"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66844"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of double vision that is worse when looking down and to the right. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her visual acuity is normal. There is no ptosis or proptosis. The double vision is most pronounced when she looks down and to the right, and improves when she tilts her head to the left shoulder. The rest of the neurological examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following extraocular muscles is most likely affected?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Superior rectus","Superior oblique","Lateral rectus","Inferior rectus","Inferior oblique"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a left superior oblique palsy, characterised by vertical diplopia that worsens in downgaze and contralateral gaze (looking to the right). The compensatory head tilt to the left shoulder is typical of this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior oblique\u003C/strong\u003E muscle, innervated by the trochlear nerve (cranial nerve IV), has primary actions of intorsion, depression, and abduction of the eye when it is in adduction. When this muscle is paralysed, patients experience vertical diplopia that is worst when looking down and to the opposite side.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior rectus\u003C/strong\u003E muscle elevates, intorts, and adducts the eye. Paralysis would cause vertical diplopia worst in upgaze, not downgaze as seen here. This muscle is innervated by the oculomotor nerve (cranial nerve III).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral rectus\u003C/strong\u003E muscle, innervated by the abducens nerve (cranial nerve VI), purely abducts the eye. Its paralysis would cause horizontal, not vertical diplopia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior rectus\u003C/strong\u003E muscle depresses, extorts, and adducts the eye. It is innervated by the inferior division of the oculomotor nerve.  Its paralysis would cause vertical diplopia worst in downgaze and ipsilateral gaze.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior oblique\u003C/strong\u003E muscle extorts, elevates, and abducts the eye when it is in adduction. The inferior oblique is innervated by the inferior division of the oculomotor nerve (cranial nerve III)\u003Cstrong\u003E. \u003C/strong\u003EIts paralysis would cause vertical diplopia worst in upgaze and contralateral gaze.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The superior oblique muscle intorts, depresses and abducts the eye when the eye is in adduction.","The trochlear nerve (cranial nerve IV) innervates only the superior oblique muscle.","Isolated superior oblique palsy typically presents with vertical diplopia that worsens on looking down and to the contralateral side."],"references":["Sekero\u011flu HT, Sanac AS, Arslan U, Sener EC. Superior oblique surgery: when and how? Clin Ophthalmol. 2013;7:1571-4. doi: 10.2147/OPTH.S46382. Epub 2013 Aug 2. PMID: 23946644; PMCID: PMC3739542.","Abdelhady A, Patel BC, Aslam S, et al. Anatomy, Head and Neck: Eye Superior Oblique Muscle. [Updated 2023 Aug 7]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537152/","Netter, F. H. (2015).\u00a0Netter\u2019s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52298"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16283"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52298"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-02T16:57:25+10:30","updatedAt":